'''William Troy Balderson''' (born January 16, 1962)<ref name=\"bioguide\">{{CongBio|B001306|inline=1}}</ref> is an American politician currently serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Ohio's 12th congressional district]], in office since September 2018. He previously served as an [[Ohio Senate|Ohio State Senator]] representing the 20th district from 2011 until his election as a U.S. Representative. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he previously was a member of the [[Ohio House of Representatives]] from 2009 to 2011.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn and raised in southeastern Ohio, Balderson graduated from [[Zanesville High School]] in 1980 and attended both Muskingum College and The [[Ohio State University]]. He lives in [[Zanesville, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Ohio Senate|url=http://www.ohiosenate.gov/senate2012/balderson/biography|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130217165655/http://www.ohiosenate.gov/senate2012/balderson/biography|dead-url=yes|archive-date=February 17, 2013|accessdate=December 17, 2012|title=Troy Balderson profile}}</ref> When incumbent [[Jim Aslanides]] became term-limited, Balderson sought the Republican nomination for state representative of the 94th Ohio House District. He won the nomination with 67.63% of the vote against Patrick Johnson.<ref>Brunner, Jennifer [http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/prohrep.aspx 2008 primary election results] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227153144/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/prohrep.aspx|archivedate=December 27, 2010|date=December 27, 2010}}</ref> \n\nBalderson faced Democrat Jennifer Stewart in the general election. Democrats hoped that Stewart would build on solid party showings from the previous election cycle.<ref>[http://www.ohiodailyblog.com/content/oh-house-94-stewart-d-face-johnston-r-and-balderson-r OH House-94: Stewart (D) to Face Johnston (R) and Balderson (R)]</ref> With 54.01% of the vote, Balderson was elected to his first term in the Ohio House of Representatives.<ref>Brunner, Jennifer [http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/ohRep_110408.aspx 2008 general election results] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916124611/http://www.sos.state.oh.us/SOS/elections/electResultsMain/2008ElectionResults/ohRep_110408.aspx |date=September 16, 2011 }} (November 4, 2008)</ref>\n\nBalderson was unopposed for his seat in the 2010 general election and won a second term.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brunner|first=Jennifer|title=Ohio Secretary of State|url=http://www.sos.state.oh.us/sos/elections/Research/electResultsMain/2010results/20101102ohouse.aspx|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\nWhile serving in the Ohio House of Representatives, Balderson was appointed to the House Finance Committee and also presided as Chairman of the Subcommittee on Agriculture and Natural Resources. In early 2010, Balderson proposed legislation that would subject Ohio Medicaid recipients to random drug tests in order to receive state benefits.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Glenn|first1=Brandon|title=Ohio House proposal would require random drug tests for Medicaid eligibility|url=https://medcitynews.com/2010/02/ohio-house-proposal-would-require-random-drug-tests-for-medicaid-eligibility/comment-page-1|website=MedCity News|accessdate=February 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Ohio Senate==\nIn late May 2011, State Senator [[Jimmy Stewart (politician)|Jimmy Stewart]] announced that he planned to resign his seat in the 20th Senate District at the end of the fiscal year.<ref>{{cite news | first = Holly | last = Richards | title = Sen. Jimmy Stewart resigning from Senate seat | date = May 25, 2011 | url = http://www.coshoctontribune.com/article/20110525/NEWS01/105250304 | work = Coshocton Tribune | accessdate = May 26, 2011}}</ref> Stewart continued his service as majority [[floor leader]] until he resigned.<ref>{{cite news | first = Bill | last = Hershey | title = State Sen. Stewart, number three leader, to resign | date = May 27, 2011 | url = http://www.daytondailynews.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/dayton/ohiopolitics/entries/2011/05/25/state_sen_stewart_number_three.html?cxtype=feedbot | work = [[Dayton Daily News]] | accessdate = May 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn July 12, 2011, Senate President [[Tom Niehaus]] announced that Balderson would be appointed to the vacant Senate seat. He was sworn into office on July 13, 2011. On November 6, 2012, Balderson won a full four-year term in his Senate Seat, defeating Democrat Teresa Scarmack by 59.79% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|last=Husted|first=John|title=Ohio Secretary of State|url=http://www2.sos.state.oh.us/pls/enrpublic/f?p=212:17:0::NO::P17_OTC:SE|accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBalderson was selected in 2014 as co-chair of a special legislative committee to review Ohio's renewable energy and energy efficiency regulations,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ohio.com/news/break-news/ohio-utility-chief-energy-savings-hard-to-measure-1.544042?localLinksEnabled=false |title=Ohio utility chief: Energy savings hard to measure|work=Akron Beacon Journal|location=Akron|date=November 25, 2014|accessdate=November 25, 2014 }}</ref> and served as the Chairman of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee while in the Senate\n\nIn November 2016, Balderson ran unopposed for re-election to the Ohio Senate, for a term ending in 2020. He will be term limited and ineligible to run for the Senate seat in 2020. He decided to run for Congress, to represent [[Ohio's 12th congressional district]].\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Energy and Natural Resources\u2014Chair\n*Finance\n*Government Oversight & Reform\n*Public Utilities\n*Finance Subcommittee on Primary & Secondary Education\n*Joint Committee on Agency Rule Review\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n====2018 special election====\n{{Main|Ohio's 12th congressional district special election, 2018}} \nBalderson was the Republican nominee for [[Ohio's 12th congressional district]] in an [[Ohio's 12th congressional district special election, 2018|August 2018 special election]] triggered by the resignation of Rep. [[Pat Tiberi]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=POLITICO |title=Balderson retains GOP hold on open House seat in Ohio |date=August 24, 2018 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/24/ohio-special-election-results-troy-balderson-795697}}</ref> He faced Democrat [[Danny O'Connor (Ohio politician)|Danny O'Connor]] in the general election. On election night, the results were too close to call, and a winner wasn't called until he was officially certified as the winner of the special election on August 24, 2018. After the remaining absentee and provisional ballots were counted, he finished 1,680 votes (0.8%) ahead of O'Connor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/08/24/ohio-special-election-results-troy-balderson-795697 |title=Balderson retains GOP hold on open House seat in Ohio |work=POLITICO |access-date=August 24, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> O'Connor called Balderson to concede in the afternoon of August 24.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dispatch.com/news/20180824/balderson-wins-ohios-12th-congressional-district-election |title=Balderson wins Ohio's 12th congressional district election |last=Wehrman |first=Jessica |date=August 24, 2018 |work=The Columbus Dispatch |access-date=August 24, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> He was sworn into office on September 5, 2018.\n\n====2018 general election====\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[United States House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology|'''Committee on Science, Space, and Technology''']]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Oversight|Subcommittee on Oversight]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Research and Technology|Subcommittee on Research and Technology]]\n* [[United States House Committee on Small Business|'''Committee on Small Business''']]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Tax and Capital Access]]\n\n==Electoral history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" | Election results\n|-\n!Year\n!Office\n!Election\n!Votes for Balderson\n!%\n!Opponent\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|2008\n|rowspan=2|[[Ohio House of Representatives]]\n|General\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |27,917\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |54%\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Jennifer Stewart\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Democrat\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |23,628\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |46%\n|-\n|2010\n|General\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |28,236\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |100%\n|Unopposed\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2012\n|rowspan=2|[[Ohio Senate]]\n|General\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |87,755\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |60%\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Teresa Scarmack\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Democrat\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |59,012\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |40%\n|-\n|2016\n|General\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |48,059\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |100%\n|Unopposed\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2018\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[United States House of Representatives]]\n|Special\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |101,772\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |50%\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Danny O'Connor\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Democrat\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |100,208\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |49%\n|-\n|2018\n|General\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Danny O'Connor\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Democrat\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Oh